docs.abstract: At the World Economic Forum, the provocative filmmaker received a warm reception for his film promoting nuclear power.
docs.snippet: At the World Economic Forum, the provocative filmmaker received a warm reception for his film promoting nuclear power.
docs.lead_paragraph: Amid the crowd gathered at the World Economic Forum, Oliver Stone — an unexpected attendee — easily stands out. The filmmaker behind “Wall Street” and “Platoon” has a history of jabbing the political, business and social elite with projects that advance controversial ideas: Think about his films focused on Vladimir Putin, Edward Snowden, John F. Kennedy and more.

headline.main: Oliver Stone Goes Nuclear at Davos

docs.abstract: Dutch privacy negotiators have spurred major changes at Google, Microsoft and Zoom, using a landmark European data protection law as a lever.
docs.snippet: Dutch privacy negotiators have spurred major changes at Google, Microsoft and Zoom, using a landmark European data protection law as a lever.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 2021, privacy consultants working for two Dutch universities issued a critical report card on Google’s education apps, a set of classroom tools like Google Docs that are used by more than 170 million students and educators worldwide.

headline.main: How the Netherlands Is Taming Big Tech
headline.print_headline: Little Netherlands Brings Tech’s Goliaths to Heel

docs.lead_paragraph: Job cuts have begun at Goldman Sachs. A wave that’s expected to grow to as many as 3,200 layoffs, one of the largest by the bank since the 2008 financial crisis, started on Tuesday, including at its premier equity capital markets division, sources told DealBook. More across-the-board cuts are expected to be announced on Wednesday.

headline.main: Big Cuts Are Coming to Goldman Sachs

docs.abstract: For decades, tech companies heralded an approach that centered on making workers happy. That’s changing fast.
docs.snippet: For decades, tech companies heralded an approach that centered on making workers happy. That’s changing fast.
docs.lead_paragraph: Silicon Valley as we know it — with its radically transparent company cultures, empowered employees, flat hierarchies and rarefied perks like nap pods and free food — is quickly disappearing. And it’s unlikely to return.

headline.main: The Era of Happy Tech Workers Is Over
headline.print_headline: The Era of Happy Tech Workers Is Over

docs.abstract: The company’s grip on ticket sales, and its move last year to cancel sales for Taylor Swift’s upcoming tour, will be a big focus of an antitrust-focused hearing.
docs.snippet: The company’s grip on ticket sales, and its move last year to cancel sales for Taylor Swift’s upcoming tour, will be a big focus of an antitrust-focused hearing.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two months after Ticketmaster canceled sales for Taylor Swift’s upcoming Eras tour, a top executive from its parent company, Live Nation Entertainment, will appear at the Senate on Tuesday to defend the company. (Ms. Swift herself is not scheduled to show up.)

headline.main: Live Nation Faces a Skeptical Senate

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: Some of the biggest tech companies have announced tens of thousands of job cuts. But even after the layoffs, their work forces are still behemoths.
docs.snippet: Some of the biggest tech companies have announced tens of thousands of job cuts. But even after the layoffs, their work forces are still behemoths.
docs.lead_paragraph: For a stretch of the pandemic, tech companies couldn’t hire fast enough. Talent wars broke out in Silicon Valley, with firms vying for software engineers, often lavishing extravagant perks on their new and would-be hires. As profits soared, executives acted as if the party would never end.

headline.main: Layoffs at Tech Giants Reverse Small Part of Pandemic Hiring Spree
headline.print_headline: Tech Giants Roll Back a Pandemic Spree
